\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background and motivations}
Variability observed in astrophysical sources is often driven by complex physical processes, making their characterization a challenging task. In particular, one-dimensional data sequences obtained from high-energy observations frequently exhibit irregular sampling, data gaps, and apparent nonstationary behavior. Under such conditions, conventional linear analysis methods may be insufficient to fully capture the underlying dynamical nature of the observed variability.

These limitations motivate the introduction of analysis frameworks that can describe temporal structures and dynamical patterns beyond simple statistical measures. Such approaches are expected to provide complementary insights into the organization and evolution of variability in astrophysical one-dimensional data sequences. In this context, both the theoretical foundation of nonlinear time series analysis and its application to observational data play essential roles.

In this study, we apply recurrence plot analysis to one-dimensional gamma-ray time series of blazars to investigate the dynamical structures underlying their observed variability. In addition to characterizing the intrinsic dynamics, we pay particular attention to the influence of data preprocessing procedures. Observational data often require interpolation to handle missing or unevenly sampled points. However, such preprocessing may artificially modify the temporal structure of the original signal.

Our analysis demonstrates that linear interpolation systematically enhances laminar structures in recurrence plots, leading to increased laminarity-related measures. This effect is observed not only in blazar gamma-ray data but also in benchmark dynamical systems with known properties, indicating that interpolation can introduce artificial temporal continuity irrespective of the underlying dynamics. These findings highlight the necessity of carefully assessing preprocessing effects when applying nonlinear time-series analysis to astronomical observations. 

\subsection{Nonlinear Time Series Analysis}
Time series analysis is a fundamental tool used across a wide range of scientific disciplines, including physics, astronomy, geophysics, economics, and biology. Its primary objective is to extract meaningful information about the underlying processes from observed temporal data. Traditional approaches are often based on linear models and statistical assumptions, which are effective for stationary systems with relatively simple dynamics.

However, many real-world systems exhibit complex behavior that violates these assumptions. Observational time series frequently display nonstationary characteristics, nonlinear interactions, and sensitivity to initial conditions. Under such circumstances, linear time series methods may fail to adequately describe the temporal evolution or intrinsic structure of the underlying dynamics, potentially obscuring important physical information.

To address these limitations, nonlinear time series analysis provides a framework that explicitly accounts for nonlinear and nonstationary properties of observed data. Rather than relying solely on linear correlations or spectral characteristics, these approaches aim to reconstruct and analyze the dynamical system that generates the time series, enabling the characterization of structural features such as determinism, temporal organization, and transitions between different dynamical regimes.

Consequently, nonlinear time series analysis offers complementary insights beyond those obtained from conventional linear techniques, particularly for observational data whose underlying dynamics are unknown.

\subsection{Application for Galaxy observation data: Blazar}
In recent years, the application of time series analysis to astronomical observations has attracted increasing attention, particularly in the study of high-energy astrophysical phenomena. Observational data in astronomy are often used to extract characteristic features for purposes such as prediction, classification, and anomaly detection. However, the physical processes underlying these observations are frequently complex and not directly accessible.

Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN) are representative examples of such systems, exhibiting strong and highly variable emission across a wide range of energies, including intense X-rays and gamma rays. Recent studies have suggested that nonlinear characteristics in AGN one-dimensional data sequences may play an important role in understanding the generation mechanisms of this high-energy emission \cite{ref1}. Despite their potential significance, these nonlinear features are difficult to capture using conventional linear analysis methods and are often misinterpreted as stochastic noise.

Blazars, a subclass of AGN with relativistic jets oriented close to the line of sight, provide particularly suitable targets for investigating such nonlinear behavior due to their pronounced variability. In this study, we apply nonlinear time series analysis to one-dimensional gamma-ray observational data of blazars to investigate their dynamical properties and assess the extent to which nonlinear structures can be identified beyond linear statistical descriptions.  

\chapter{Related work}
Previous　studies on the temporal variability of blazars have primarily focused on the statistical characterization of light curves using power spectral density analysis and related linear techniques. These approaches have successfully described the global statistical properties of variability, such as power-law noise behavior, and have contributed to phenomenological classifications of blazar variability. However, they provide limited information about the underlying dynamical mechanisms responsible for the observed fluctuations.

To go beyond purely statistical descriptions, several studies have explored the applications of nonlinear time series analysis to AGN and blazar light curves. In particular, Bhatta \textit{et al.} (2020) performed a comprehensive nonlinear analysis of decade-long Fermi/LAT gamma-ray observations of 20 blazars using recurrence quantification analysis (RQA). By evaluating recurrence-based measures such as determinism, average diagonal length, and entropy. They investigated whether the observed gamma-ray variability is predominantly deterministic or stochastic in nature. Their results suggested that blazar variability is generally characterized by a mixture of deterministic and stochastic processes, with some sources exhibiting significant deterministic content.

In addition to characterizing dynamical regimes, recurrence-based approaches have also been used to estimate characteristic timescales associated with the persistence of dynamical states. The vertical structures in the recurrence plots were interpreted as trapping timescales, providing insight into the temporal organization of variability on timescales of several weeks. These findings have been discussed in the context of disk-jet coupling and the physical origin of high-energy emission.

Despite these advances, several issues remain unresolved. First recurrence quantification measures are known to depend sensitively on the choice of analysis parameters, including embedding dimension, recurrence threshold, and minimum line length. As a result, direct comparisons between different datasets or studies can be challenging. Second, observational blazar light curves often contain uneven sampling and missing data, requiring interpolation or other preprocessing steps. Such procedures may systematically alter the recurrence structure of the one-dimensional data sequences and consequently bias the interpretation of recurrence-based measures.

While previous work has acknowledged these limitations, a systematic investigation of how preprocessing and measure selection affect recurrence-based classification and interpretation of blazar one-dimensional data sequences remains limited. Therefore, further analysis is required to clarify the robustness and interpretability of recurrence-based indicators when applied to real observational data.



\chapter{Analysis Methods}

\section{Reconstruction of attractor}
In this chapter, we describe the nonlinear time series analysis methods employed in this study. Specifically, attractor reconstruction based on Takens' embedding theorem, parameter estimation methods, and recurrence-based analysis are introduced in detail.

The data used in this study consist of approximately ten years of observations obtained by Fermi/LAT, with most sources having observation periods about from 430 to 510 weeks. Since the observational time series includes missing values, linear interpolation was applied to obtain uniformly sampled data suitable for nonlinear time series analysis.

To investigate the underlying dynamical structure embedded in the observed one-dimensional time series, the attractor was reconstructed using Takens' embedding theorem. This theorem states that the dynamics of a deterministic system can be reconstructed from a single observed variable using delay coordinate embedding.

The reconstructed state vector is defined as follows and given by Eq. (3.1),
\begin{equation}
X(t) = (x(t), x(t-\tau), x(t - 2\tau), ...., x(t - (m - 1)\tau)),
\end{equation}
where $\tau$ denotes the delay time and $m$ is the embedding dimension.
Here, $x(t)$ denotes the observed scalar time series, which is treated as a continuous time representationof the observation data.

To apply Eq. (3.1), an appropriate value of $\tau$ and $m$ must be determined. In this study, the delay time $\tau$ was determined using the mutual information method, which evaluates the degree of nonlinear dependence between $x(t)$ and $x(t + \tau)$. The  embedding dimension $m$ was estimated using an improved version of the L. Cao method proposed by Itoh \textit{et al}. \cite{ref2}, which enables the reliable determination of the minimum embedding dimension.


\subsection{Estimation time delay:  Mutual information }
To reconstruct the phase space from a one-dimensional time series, an appropriate delay time \tau must be determined. In this study, the delay time was estimated using mutual information, which evaluates the statistical dependence between the present value x(t) and the delay value x(t+\tau).

Mutual information measures how much information about the delay state can be inferred from the present state, and thus reflects the degree of dependency between the two. Unlike the autocorrelation function, which captures only linear correlations, mutual information accounts for both linear and nonlinear dependencies, making it suitable for analyzing nonlinear dynamical systems.

In practice, mutual information was computed for a range of delay times \tau, and the first local minimum was selected as the optimal delay time. This minimum corresponds to a balance where the delayed components of the reconstructed state vector are neither redundant nor independent, ensuring an appropriate separation of dynamical information for phase space reconstruction.

\subsection{Estimation embedding dimension: L.Cao method}
In this study, the minimum embedding dimension is determined as the smallest dimension at which the evaluation index E1(m) exhibits convergence, based on the L. Cao method.  
In a reconstructed phase space, if the embedding dimension $m$ is insufficient, state vectors that are not truly close in the original system may be incorrectly identified as neighbors, resulting in so-called false neighbors.

As the embedding dimension increases, the geometrical structure of the underlying dynamical system is progressively unfolded, and the distance relationship among neighboring points are expected to become stable.

The L. Cao method determines the minimum embedding dimension by evaluating the stability of distances between neighboring reconstructed vectors as the embedding dimension is increased.
In the L. Cao method, reconstructed vectors are first constructed from a scalar time series using a delay coordinate embedding based on Takens' embedding theorem.

Given a delay time $\tau$ and an embedding dimension $m$, the reconstructed vector ${x}_i^{(m)}$. It is defined as Eq. (3.2) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
{X}_i^{(m)} = ({x}_i, {x}_{i+\tau}, {x}_{i+2\tau}, \ldots, {x}_{i+(m-1)\tau}), \quad i = 1, 2, \ldots, N-(m-1)\tau.
\end{equation}
For each reconstructed vector ${X}_i^{(m)}$, the nearest neighbor ${X}_{n(i,m)}^{(m)}$ is defined in the $m$ dimensional embedding space based on the Euclidean distance.

The change in distance between neighboring vectors when the embedding dimension increases from $m$ to $m+1$ is then quantified by the following distance ratio. It is defined as Eq. (3.3) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
a(i,m) = \frac{||{X}_{i+1}^{(m)} - {X}_{n(i,m)+1}^{(m)}||}{||{X}_i^{(m)} - {X}_{n(i,m)}^{(m)}||}.
\end{equation}
Here, the denominator represents the distance between a reconstructed vector ${X}_i^{(m)}$ and its nearest neighbor in the $m$-dimensional embedding. In contrast, the numerator represents the corresponding distance after increasing the embedding dimension by one. 

The evaluation index $E_1(m)$ is defined as the average of the distance ratio $a(i,m)$ over all valid reconstructed vectors. It is defined as Eq. (3.4) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
E_1(m) = \frac{1}{N - m\tau}\sum_{i=1}^{N-m\tau}{a(i,m)}.
\end{equation}
When the embedding dimension is small, the influence of false neighbors causes $E_1(m)$ to vary significantly. 

As the embedding dimension increases, the neighborhood relationship in the reconstructed phase space becomes stable, and $E_1(m)$ converges to an approximately constant value.

Based on this property, the L. Cao method determines the minimum embedding dimension as the smallest value of $m$ at which the evaluation index $E_1(m)$ converges. In this study, the embedding dimension is selected according to this criterion.

However, since the L. Cao method evaluates distance using only a single nearest neighbor, it may be sensitive to noise and outliers in the series data. In the following section, the Itho method \cite{ref2}, which improves robustness by considering multiple nearest neighbors, is introduced.

The Itho method is an extension of the L. Cao method that improves robustness against measurement noise by considering multiple nearest neighbors instead of a single one. While the L. Cao method evaluates the distance change using the closest neighbor, the Itho method evaluates the average distance ratio over $k$ nearest neighbors, thereby suppressing the influence of noise and outliers.

For each reconstructed vector ${X}_i^{(m)}$, let ${X}_{ij}^{(m)}$ $i = 1, 2, \ldots, k$ denote its $k$ nearest neighbors in the $m$-dimensional reconstructed space. The average distance ratio is defined as Eq. (3.5) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
a(i,m) = \frac{1}{k}\sum_{j=1}^{k}\frac{||{X}_{i}^{(m+1)} - {X}_{ij}^{(m+1)}||}{||{X}_i^{(m)} - {X}_{ij}^{(m)}||}.
\end{equation}
By averaging over multiple neighbors, this quantity provides a more stable local evaluation of the distance change when the embedding dimension is increased.
The evaluation index ${E_1^{Itho}{(m)}}$ is obtained by averaging $a(i,m)$ over all reconstructed vectors. It is defined as Eq. (3.6) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
{E_1^{Itho}{(m)}} = \frac{1}{N - m\tau}\sum_{i=1}^{N-m\tau}{a(i,m)}.
\end{equation}

Similar to the L. Cao method, this index exhibits a convergent behavior as the embedding dimension increases. The minimum embedding dimension is determined as the smallest dimension at which ${E_1^{Itho}{(m)}}$ converges.
In addition, since the applicability of nonlinear time series analysis presupposes an underlying deterministic structure, the Itho method is employed to evaluate whether the analyzed time series exhibits deterministic or stochastic behavior through the indicator $E_2(m)$.


First, the quantity $\beta_2(m)$ is the average distance between the future components of neighboring reconstructed vectors. It is defined as Eq. (3.7) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
{\beta_2(m) = \frac{1}{N-m\tau}\sum_{i=1}^{N-m\tau}\frac{1}{k}\sum_{j=1}^{k}|x_{i+m\tau}-x_{j(i,m)+m\tau}|}.
\end{equation}

Using this quantity, the indicator $E_2(m)$ is defined as the ratio. It is defined as Eq. (3.8) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
E_2(m) = \frac{\beta_2(m+1)}{\beta_2(m)}.
\end{equation}

If the time series has a deterministic structure, neighboring vectors tend to have similar future components, and thus $E_2(m)$ deviates from unity. In contrast, for stochastic or random item series, the future components are independent of the current state, resulting in $E_2(m) \approx 1$.

Therefore, $E_2(m)$ serves as an indicator for distinguishing deterministic dynamics from stochastic behavior, complementing the embedding dimension determination based on $E_1(m)$.

\section{Recurrence plot}
The recurrence matrix defines a recurrence plot (RP), which represents the recurrence structure of trajectories in the reconstructed state space. It is defined as Eq. (3.9) is described as follows,
\begin{equation}
R_{i,j} = {\Theta(\epsilon-||{x_i-x_j}||)},
\end{equation}
where $x_i$ and $x_j$ denote state vectors obtained by phase space reconstruction, and $\epsilon$ is a threshold distance. An element $R_{i,j} = 1$ indicates that two states are sufficiently close and is represented as a black dot, whereas $R_{i,j} = 0$ is shown as a white dot. By visualizing this binary matrix on the time-time plane, the recurrence plot reveals recurrence patterns and provides insight into the nonlinear and nonstationary dynamics of the time series. Furthermore, the geometrical structures observed in the recurrence plot form the basis of recurrence quantification analysis (RQA), enabling objective and quantitative characterization of the underlying dynamical behavior.

\section{Recurrence quantification analysis}
Recurrence Quantification Analysis (RQA) is a nonlinear time series analysis framework that quantifies structures observed in recurrence plots and enables an objective characterization of complex dynamical systems. Unlike conventional linear analysis methods, RQA does not require the assumption of stationarity or linearity, making it particularly suitable for real-world observational data that often exhibit nonlinear behavior, nonstationarity, and noise contamination.

A recurrence plot visualizes the times at which the trajectory of a dynamical system returns to similar regions in the reconstructed phase space, thereby revealing intrinsic dynamical structures that may not be apparent in the original time series. Isolated recurrence points represent local state recurrences, whereas extended line-like structures, including diagonal, vertical, and horizontal lines, reflect deterministic evolution, temporal correlations, and laminar or intermittent behavior inherent to nonlinear dynamics.

RQA translates these genometrical features into a set of quantitative measures, allowing a statistical and comparative evaluation of nonlinear dynamical properties across different time series and processing conditions. In the following section, individual RQA measures are introduced, and their relationship to specific recurrence structures and dynamical characteristics is discussed in detail.
\subsection{Means of indicators of RQA}
In this study, several standard Recurrence Quantification Analysis (RQA) measures are employed to characterize different aspects of the underlying nonlinear dynamics. The recurrence rate(RR) represents the density of recurrence points in the recurrence plot and provides a global measure of how frequently the system revisits similar states in the reconstructed state space. As such, RR reflects the overall recurrence tendency of the system and is sensitive to changes in the distribution of states, although it does not explicitly account for temporal ordering.

Determinism (DET) quantifies the fraction of recurrence points that form diagonal line structures in the recurrence plot. Diagonal lines arise when segments of the trajectory evolve similarly over consecutive time steps, and therefore, DET serves as an indicator of temporal predictability and the degree of deterministic organization in the dynamics. Higher DET values generally correspond to more regular or deterministic behavior, whereas lower values indicate increased stochasticity or irregular dynamics.

The diagonal ratio (DEratio), average diagonal line length (L), and diagonal line entropy (EN) further characterize the statistical properties of diagonal line structures. DEratio reflects the relative dominance of diagonal structures compared to isolated recurrence points, while L represents the typical duration over which similar dynamical evolution persists. The entropy measure EN quantifies the diversity of diagonal line lengths and thus captures the complexity provide a more detailed description of the structure and richness of deterministic dynamics beyond what is captured by DET alone.

In contrast, laminarity (LAM) and trapping time (TT) are based on vertical line structures in the recurrence plot and characterize a different aspect of the dynamics. Vertical lines indicate that the system remains in a similar state over successive time steps, which is commonly associated with laminar or intermittent behavior. LAM measures the proportion of recurrence points forming vertical structuresm while TT represents the average length of these vertical lines, corresponding to the typical residence time of the system in a specific state. These measures are particularly useful for quantifying intermittency and the strength of the laminar phase in nonlinear and nonstationary dynamics.

