\section{Embedding parameter estimation}
Figure 4.2 shows the result of embedding dimension estimation using the Itho method.
The quantity $E1(m)$ exhibits a rapid decrease with increasing embedding dimension and becomes nearly constant for $m\ge4$. This behavior indicates that the false nearest neighbors are sufficiently resolved at this dimension, and thus the minimum embedding dimension is determined as $m=4$.

\begin{figure}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{cao_compare_1ES1959_650_lc_liner.png}
    \caption{Minimum embedding dimension of 1ES1959\_650 estimated by Itho method}
    \label{8rqa}
\end{figure}

In this study, the Lorenz system was used as a reference to verify the robustness of the Itho method against observational noise and outliers. The convergence behavior of $E1(m)$ remains nearly unchanged even when noise is added, indicating that the minimum embedding dimension can be stably estimated in noisy conditions.

Based on this result, an embedding dimension of $m=4$ is adopted for the subsequent construction of recurrence plots and recurrence quantification analysis.

