The recurrence plot reveals a distinct block-like structure around the same interval along the main diagonal. This region is dominated by dense vertical and horizontal line structures, indicating prolonged residence of the system in similar states over consecutive time steps.

Such structures are characteristic of enhanced laminarity in the recurrence plot and reflect increased temporal continuity introduced by the interpolation process. Similar block-like laminar regions were identified in other analyzed sources at different time intervals, suggesting that linear interpolation systematically influences laminarity-related recurrence structures across the dataset.

\section{Verification using systems with known dynamical}
Figure 4.4 illustrates the effect of linear interpolation on laminarity-related recurrence quantification measures for eight dynamical systems with known structures. The analyzed systems include deterministic systems (Lorenz attractor and sine wave), a chaotic system (logistic map), and stochastic processes (Brownian motion and white noise). In addition, noise-added systems of the Lorenz attractor, sine wave, and logistic map were also considered to examine the effect of observation noise. For each system, missing values were  introduced at rates ranging from 0\% to 90\% and reconstructed using linear interpolation. Recurrence plots were constructed from the interpolation time series, and the mean laminarity (mLAM) was evaluated for each condition.

\begin{figure}[ht]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{trend_mLAM.png}
    \caption{Effect of Linear Interpolation on Laminarity in Known Dynamical Systems}
    \label{8rqa}
\end{figure}

As shown in Fig. 4.4, a systematic increase in mean laminarity with an increase in the missing rate is observed across most dynamical systems. Intrinsically smooth and deterministic systems, such as the sine wave and the Lorenz attractor, maintain consistently high mLAM values regardless of the missing rate. In contrast, systems characterized by chaotic or stochastic dynamics, including the logistic map and white noise, exhibit a pronounced rise in mLAM as the missing rate increases. Noise-added three systems show similar tendencies, although with slightly reduced absolute laminarity values compared to their noise-free counterparts.

These results indicate that linear interpolation progressively introduces artificial temporal continuity into the reconstructed time series as the proportion of missing data increases. This imposed smoothness enhances vertical line structures in the recurrence plots, leading to elevated laminarity-related RQA measures even for systems that are not intrinsically laminar. 

