These results indicate that mDEratio preserves variability even in highly deterministic regimes, enabling a more graded classification.


These results indicate that mDET tends to saturate at high values and therefore provides limited discriminative power for blazar time series. In contrast, the mDEratio preserves variability even within highly deterministic regimes.

This advantage arises from the definition of the DEratio, which incorporates not only the abundance of diagonal structures but also their distributional properties, making it more sensitive to subtle changes in recurrence organization. 
As a result, the mDEratio enables a more informative graded classification without relying on sharp cluster boundaries.

Based on this mDE-ratio classification, we next examine the one-dimensional data sequence characteristics of each group to explore how these differences are reflected in the light curves.

