This allows a direct comparison of structural characteristics across deterministic, chaotic, and stochastic dynamics without reintroducing detailed system descriptions. The distributions of the reference systems reveal systematic differences in their recurrence structures.
Systems with strongly deterministic and organized dynamics tend to occupy regions associated with higher structural complexity. In contrast, stochastic processes are distributed toward regions characterized by weaker and less coherent recurrence patterns. 

Intermediate behaviors are observed for low-dimensional chaotic and periodic systems, with noise-contaminated variants showing gradual shifts toward more stochastic-like distributions.

By comparing the reference systems with the observational data in the same parameter spaces. A qualitative correspondence between the mDEratio-based groups and the known dynamical systems can be identified.

The High group tends to be located closer to reference systems with strong deterministic and structurally complex dynamics, such as the Lorenz attractor, whereas the Low group shows greater proximity to stochastic processes, including white noise and Brownian motion. The Mid group occupies an intermediate region, overlapping with periodic or low-dimensional chaotic systems such as the sine wave and logistic map.


\subsection{Validation using the Itho method (E2 analysis)}
To further substantiate the classification inferred from the RQA-based parameter spaces, we next examine the behavior of the $E_2(m)$ indicator introduced in the Itho method. This analysis is performed for representative one-dimensional sequences in each group.

Here, the $E_2(m)$ method is used as an independent diagnostic to assess whether the reconstructed dynamics exhibit deterministic saturation behavior or stochastic characteristics.

Figure 4.10 shows the $E_2(m)$ curves for one-dimensional sequences belonging to the High group, which were identified as being close to deterministic reference systems such as the Lorenz attractor.

