These data show $E_2(m)$ values remaining close to unity over a wide range of embedding dimensions, indicating the absence of saturation and reflecting the effectively infinite-dimensional nature of stochastic dynamics.

For the Mid group, no single characteristic $E_2(m)$ behavior was observed. Instead, some one-dimensional data sequences exhibited weak saturation tendencies similar to those seen in deterministic systems, while others showed behavior closer to stochastic processes. This mixed behavior is consistent with the intermediate position of the Mid group in the RQA-based parameter spaces, overlapping with periodic or low-dimensional chaotic systems as well as more stochastic dynamics.

Taken together, these results demonstrate that the $E_2(m)$ analysis independently supports the RQA-based grouping. One-dimensional data sequences classified as deterministic-like or stochastic-like in the recurrence-based parameter spaces exhibit corresponding characteristics in their $E_2(m)$ behavior, reinforcing the interpretation that the observed grouping reflects genuine differences in the underlying dynamical structures.


\chapter{Conclusion}
\section{Findings}
In this study, RP and RQA were applied to one-dimensional gamma-ray time series of blazars to investigate their underlying dynamical structures. By systematically analyzing both observational data and reference systems with known dynamics, we demonstrated that linear interpolation significantly modifies recurrence structures. In particular, it enhances laminar patterns and leads to increased laminarity-related measures.

The effect of linear interpolation was shown to be systematic and robust across different dynamical regimes. Verification using deterministic, chaotic, and stochastic reference systems revealed that increasing missing rates reconstructed by linear interpolation introduce artificial temporal continuity, leading to elevated laminarity even in systems that are not intrinsically laminar. These results indicate that laminarity-related RQA measures are highly sensitive to preprocessing procedures and may reflect interpolation-induced structures rather than intrinsic dynamical properties.

Furthermore, the classification of blazar time series based solely on DET was found to have limited discriminative power due to saturation in the high-determinism regime. To address this limitation, the DEratio was introduced as an alternative indicator. The mDEratio preserved variability across the dataset and enabled a more graded classification of blazar time series, which was consistent with structural differences observed in recurrence-based parameter spaces.

Comparison with reference dynamical systems showed that the mDEratio-based groups qualitatively correspond to deterministic-like, intermediate, and stochastic-like dynamics. This interpretation was independently supported by  the $E_2(m)$ indicator introduced in the Itho method. This analysis demonstrated saturation behavior for the high-group one-dimensional data sequences and near-unity behavior for the low group series, consistent with deterministic and stochastic dynamics, respectively

Taken together, these findings indicate that recurrence-based characterization of blazar gamma-ray variability can provide meaningful insight into the underlying dynamical structures. At the same time, the results clearly demonstrate that preprocessing procedures, particularly linear interpolation, can strongly influence recurrence structures and associated RQA measures. Therefore, careful consideration of preprocessing effects is essential for reliable dynamical interpretation of one-dimensional astronomical data sequences.

.
\section{Future improvement} 
The present study demonstrated that preprocessing procedures, particularly linear interpolation, can strongly influence recurrence structures and associated RQA measures in blazar gamma-ray time series. These results suggest that laminarity-related features may partly reflect preprocessing artifacts rather than intrinsic physical dynamics.

As a future improvement, it is important to further assess interpolation effects in recurrence-based analysis. Systematic comparison of different interpolation methods, as well as approaches that account for irregular sampling, may help to distinguish artificial structures introduced by preprocessing from physically meaningful dynamical features. Such efforts are expected to improve the reliability of the dynamics interpretation of one-dimensional astronomical data sequences.


